Thailand's Phuket airport reopens after Tsunami threat
2012-04-12 08:00:25 GMT
BANGKOK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Services at Phuket Airport resumed Thursday after being shut down during a Tsunami warning in six coastal provinces sparked by a 8.6-magnitude earthquake off Indonesia, an official said.The airport was reopened Wednesday night soon after Tsunami watch was lifted by the National Disaster Warning Center, said Bang-orurat Shinaprayon, director of the Tourism Authority of Thailand.The center on Wednesday afternoon issued a Tsunami warning to the six provinces along the Andaman Sea -- Krabi, Phuket, Phang Nga, Ranong, Satun and Trang; however, it later revoked the warning at about 8 p.m. local time when it was clear the earthquake off Indonesia did not generate disastrous Tsunami.Phuket International Airport was closed for several hours during the disaster scare, with more than 15 flights delayed.
